      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
      "body" : "@LicenseQ: I don&#39;t know if this statement was correct at the time you wrote it, but it&#39;s not correct for any recent release of Java. The implementation of String.substring is smarter than that: it does not copy the character buffer of the original string, it simply creates a new String object pointing to the same buffer and uses a nonzero &quot;offset&quot; field to indicate that the string doesn&#39;t start from the beginning of the buffer. Substring allocates a String object containing three ints (count, hash and offset) and a reference to the pre-existing buffer, nothing more."
    } ],
